== Overview == The Shibayama Haniwa Festival was initially conceived by local volunteers as a way to unite residents divided by the {{ill|Narita Airport dispute|ja|成田空港問題|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Narita Airport dispute|qq=}}.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Curator in My Town: Shibayama Kofun Haniwa Museum, Over 500 Kofun Once Existed / Chiba|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20170807/ddl/k12/040/136000c|website=Mainichi Shimbun|accessdate=2019-03-09|date=2017-08-07}}</ref> Officially described as a festival "born to reflect on and recall the wonders of ancient times,"<ref>{{Cite web|title=The 35th Shibayama Haniwa Festival is being held!|url=http://shibayama-kankou.com/info/614/|website=Shibayama Town Tourism Portal|accessdate=2019-03-09|publisher=Shibayama Town Tourism Association}}</ref> it was first held on October 31, 1982 (Showa 57)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.town.shibayama.lg.jp/cmsfiles/contents/0000002/2489/2015ShibayamaYouran_history_p8-15.pdf|title=Sixty Years of Shibayama History|accessdate=2019-03-09|publisher=Shibayama Town|format=PDF}}</ref> and contributed significantly to fostering harmony among local residents.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Photo Album: The Showa Era in Sanbu|year=2012|publisher=Iki Publishing|page=130}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title="Slip Back in Time in the 'Land of Ancient Tombs': Shibayama Town"|url=https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXMZO24736060W7A211C1CC0000/|website=Nikkei Electronic Edition|accessdate=2019-03-09}}</ref>
Today, it is positioned as a community revitalization event, held annually on the second Sunday of November.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|title=Haniwa Festival Main Page|url=http://www.haniwakan.com/matsuri/top.html|website=Haniwa Museum Website|accessdate=2019-03-09|publisher=Shibayama Kofun Haniwa Museum}}</ref>
The festival draws inspiration from Shibayama's iconic {{ill|ancient Kofuns|ja|古墳群|1=Kofun cluster|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/ancient Kofuns|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun cluster|qq=}} and [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]]. The central concept involves interaction with "ancient people" who have descended into modern times to make a promise with the people of Shibayama to create a kind and livable town. During the festival, local residents, including elementary and middle school students, dress as ancient people to perform rituals and parades. The event concludes with the ancient people delivering messages to modern attendees before "ascending to the heavens."<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web|title=Festivals and Events|url=http://shibayama-kankou.com/event/|website=Shibayama Town Tourism Portal|accessdate=2019-03-09|publisher=Shibayama Town Tourism Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Travel Back in Time to Ancient Japan, Featuring AKB's Nagao-san: Shibayama Haniwa Festival|url=https://www.chibanippo.co.jp/news/local/224238|website=Chiba Nippo Online|accessdate=2019-03-09|publisher=Chiba Nippo Online|date=2014-11-10}}</ref>
== See Also == * [[:en:Shibayama Kofun Haniwa Museum|Shibayama Kofun Haniwa Museum]] * [[:en:Shibayama Kofun Cluster|Shibayama Kofun Cluster]], {{ill|Yamada-Houma Kofun Cluster|ja|山田・宝馬古墳群|1=Yamada-Hōma Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamada-Houma Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamada-Hōma Kofun Cluster|qq=}}, and {{ill|Takada No. 2 Kofun|ja|高田二号墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takada No. 2 Kofun|qq=}} * {{ill|Shibayama Haniwa Road|ja|芝山はにわ道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibayama Haniwa Road|qq=}} * {{ill|Motohide Murayama|ja|村山元英|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Motohide Murayama|qq=}} * {{ill|Shuji Doi|ja|土井脩司|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shuji Doi|qq=}} == References == {{Reflist}} == External Links == * [https://www.town.shibayama.lg.jp/0000004151.html Shibayama Town Official Website - Tourism & Events - Shibayama Haniwa Festival] * [https://cir.nii.ac.jp/crid/1050001338458012928 Research Paper: "Festival and Regional Identity: Case Study Analysis of the Shibayama Haniwa Festival"]
